      "role": "user",
      "content": "got it. so i should add lime. i'm just worried that something in the soil is actually stealing the nutrients before the plants can even get to them, if that makes sense? like is there anything that would cause the nutrients to just disappear or get sucked away like that?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Absolutely, that makes sense. In the soil, there can be a variety of factors that might cause nutrients to become unavailable to your plants. One possibility is the presence of certain minerals, like aluminum or manganese, which can become more soluble and toxic in acidic conditions, effectively \"stealing\" nutrients from the plants. Another issue could be the presence of high levels of organic matter or clay, which can tie up nutrients, making them less available to your plants.\n\nTo address these concerns, you could consider adding organic matter like compost to improve soil structure and nutrient-holding capacity. Also, consider using a balanced, slow-release fertilizer that can provide a steady supply of nutrients over time. Regular soil testing can help you monitor nutrient levels and adjust your fertilization and soil amendment practices accordingly. Remember, it's essential to maintain a healthy balance; too much of any one thing can be just as problematic as too little. Keep an eye on your plants and soil, and adjust your care as needed to keep them thriving.",
